OHI-Northeast: Trampling Pressure Data Prep

Compiled on Tue Oct 15 15:32:12 2019 by verstaen

Summary

This code calculates the effects of beach trampling using population density along the coast as a proxy.

Data

GeoTiff files were downloaded from https://sedac.ciesin.columbia.edu/data/set/usgrid-summary-file1-2010/metadata Octover 15th 2019

The data is at 1km2 resolution. Since we are only looking at total population that means #people/km2

Methods

knitr::opts_chunk$set(fig.width = 10, fig.height = 8, fig.path = 'figs/', message = FALSE, warning = FALSE)

## create one ne raster
northeast_rast <- raster::raster("northeast.tif") %>%
  projectRaster(crs = us_alb, over = FALSE, progress="text") %>% 
  crop(ne_ext)

## check it out!
plot(northeast_rast)

We are creating a coastal buffer that includes our coastline and 25 miles inland. I chose 25 miles because that is what Casey did in BC, but we can discuss if this makes sense

## create a buffer 1 km along all state waters to get the beaches
buffer_1km_coastal <-  read_sf("~/github/ne-prep/spatial/shapefiles/state_waters.shp")  %>% 
  st_transform(us_alb) %>% 
  st_buffer(40233.6) %>%  ## data in meters; using a 25 miles buffer
  st_union() %>% 
  st_as_sf() 

plot(buffer_1km_coastal)

## create blank raster for rasterizing
r <- raster(crs = us_alb, ne_ext, res = 1000)
r[r] <- 1

## convert to a raster
buffer_rast <- fasterize(buffer_1km_coastal, r) %>% 
  crop(ne_ext)

Now we want to keep only the population density data that falls into our 25 miles within the coastline raster

## keep only the areas 1km along the shorelines
ne_pop_coast <- northeast_rast %>% 
  raster::resample(buffer_rast, method = "ngb") %>% ## match the extents
  mask(buffer_rast) %>% 
  calc(fun = function(x){ifelse(x < 0, 0, x)}) ## there are negative numbers in this data for some reason

plot(ne_pop_coast)

summary(ne_pop_coast) # The max value is very large, this is because of Manhattan

Region score

Create a raster with our states rgn_ids

## we want a raster with the region names so that we can ID the regions. This is the only file I found wiht the state land, and not just water, and it doesn't have have N/S MA. ask Jamie
ne_states_ne <- ne_states %>% 
  filter(NAME %in% c("Maine", "New York", "Rhode Island", "Connecticut", "New Hampshire", "Massachusetts")) %>% 
  mutate(zone = case_when(NAME == "Maine" ~ 6,
                          NAME == "New York" ~ 10,
                          NAME == "Rhode Island" ~ 11,
                          NAME == "Connecticut" ~ 5,
                          NAME == "New Hampshire" ~ 9,
                          NAME == "Massachusetts" ~7)) # will need to apply the same score for MA 8 later

ne_states_rast <- fasterize(ne_states_ne, r, field = "zone") %>% 
  crop(ne_ext)

plot(ne_states_rast)

Extract data for each region

# extract data for each region:
pop_stats <- zonal(ne_pop_coast, ne_states_rast, fun="mean", na.rm=TRUE, progress="text")
## 
  |                                                                       
  |                                                                 |   0%
  |                                                                       
  |================================                                 |  50%
pop_stats_2 <- data.frame(pop_stats) %>% 
  rename(rgn_id = zone,
         avg_people_per_km2 = mean)

Calculate presssure scores Here using max number of people per square miles as a pressure of 1 and rescaling all other values to it. Need to figure out if this is the right reference point to use.

ref <- ne_pop_coast %>% 
  getValues() %>%
  na.omit() %>% 
  max()

prs_trampling <-pop_stats_2 %>% 
  mutate(ref = ref,
         score = avg_people_per_km2/ref)
